A circular garden has a radius of 10 meters. Alice starts at a point on the circumference and walks along the edge of the garden at a constant speed. Bob starts at the center of the garden and walks straight to Alice's starting point. If Alice completes one full lap around the garden and Bob reaches Alice at the same time, what is the speed of Alice if Bob's speed is 1 meter per second?

[asy]
unitsize(0.15cm);
pair A,B,C;
A=(10,0);
B=(0,0);
C=dir(180-9.5);
draw(Arc(A,10,0,180));
draw(B--A);
draw(C--B);
label("Alice",(10,0),SE);
label("Bob",(0,0),S);
label("10",(A+C)/2,W);
[/asy]

A square garden has an area of 144 square meters. You need to plant flowers in it such that each flower requires 1 square meter. How many different ways can you plant 12 flowers in the garden if the flowers can be planted in rows and columns of any size as long as the area is exactly 12?

Two flowers cannot occupy the same area. Also, consider rotations and reflections of the planting layout as identical. How many distinct layouts are there?

\boxed{2}

A square park has a side length of 200 meters. There is a circular fountain with a radius of 10 meters exactly in the center of the park. If you walk along the boundary of the park and stop at the point where you are closest to the fountain, what is the distance you walked from your starting point at the corner of the park?

[asy]
filldraw(circle((100,100),10),gray);
filldraw((0,0)--(400,0)--(400,400)--(0,400)--cycle,white);
dot((100,100));
label("100 m",(100,150),S);
label("100 m",(250,100),S);
label("100 m",(100,450),N);
label("100 m",(0,100),W);
label("Park",(200,120),S);
label("Fountain",(100,100),N);
[/asy]

A square and four circles, each with radius 1, are arranged as shown. What is the area of the square?
[asy]
size(100);
defaultpen(linewidth(0.7));
pair O, A, B, C, D, P, Q, R, S;
O = (0,0);
A = O + dir(-45);
B = rotate(90,O)*A;
C = rotate(90,O)*B;
D = rotate(90,O)*C;
P = (sqrt(2)/2,0);
Q = P + A;
R = P + B;
S = P + C;
filldraw(Circle(O,1),gray(0.7));
draw(A--B--C--D--cycle,linewidth(1));
draw(P--Q--R--S--P,linewidth(1));
[/asy]

A rectangular garden has a length that is twice its width. A path of uniform width surrounds the garden, increasing the total area to 144 square meters beyond the area of the garden alone. If the outer dimensions of the garden including the path are 12 meters by 24 meters, what is the width of the path?

[asy]
unitsize(0.15inch);
defaultpen(linewidth(0.7));
draw((0,0)--(24,0)--(24,12)--(0,12)--cycle);
draw(((0,9)--(24,9))--((3,0)--(3,12)));
label("12 m",(12,0),S);
label("24 m",(0,6),W);
[/asy]
